            <div type="edition" subtype="transcription" ana="b1">
                <p><supplied reason="lost">Ἰ</supplied>ωέζαρος <gap reason="lost" quantity="5" unit="character" precision="low"/>ος
                        <expan><abbr>κ</abbr><ex>αὶ</ex></expan> Θεω<lb break="no"/><supplied reason="lost">κ</supplied>τίστα τε· Ὑγιένων
                            <expan><abbr>κτίσ</abbr><ex>τη</ex><abbr>ς</abbr></expan>
               <lb/>
               <supplied reason="lost">ἔπ</supplied>ρασσε ἄμα Πομπυλίᾳ<lb/>
               <supplied reason="lost">τοῦ</supplied> <supplied reason="lost">Χρι</supplied>στοῦ θεράποντες</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" ana="b1">
                <p> Ioezer, [...]os and Theo[c]tista; Hygienon, builder (of the tomb), made (this)
                    together with Pompilia, servants of Christ.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" ana="b1">
                <p>Two different interpretations can be suggested for this text. One interpretation
                    is that all the persons mentioned together were responsible for the hewing and
                    decoration of the tomb. Otherwise, the first three names might refer to three
                    persons buried in the tomb – probably the first three deceased who were buried
                    in the cave after it was adopted for burial in the Late Roman period – while
                    Hygienon and Pompilia, in all likelihood a married couple, were responsible for
                    decorating the burial cave and painting the inscription. </p>
            </div>
